{
  "citation_key": "yeverechyahu_2025_github_copilot",
  "authors": [
    "Doron Yeverechyahu",
    "Raveesh Mayya",
    "Gal Oestreicher-Singer"
  ],
  "title": "The Impact of Large Language Models on Open-Source Innovation: Evidence from GitHub Copilot",
  "year": 2025,
  "venue": "working paper",
  "study_design_description": "The study leverages a natural experiment around the selective rollout of GitHub Copilot in October 2021, where certain programming languages (Python, Rust) were supported while others (R, Haskell) were not. The main identification strategy employs a Two-Way Fixed Effect (TWFE) model within a differences-in-differences framework using Propensity Score Matching with nearest neighbor matching. Alternative identification uses Synthetic Difference in Differences. A lead-lag model is employed to verify parallel trends assumptions. Data consists of all activities on repositories across four languages tracked from October 2019 to December 2022, including over 1.1 million commits.",
  "primary_task_description": "Open-source software development where developers commit code changes to repositories, accompanied by comment messages detailing the changes. The study analyzes the types of innovation through two complementary approaches: (1) a code-based approach detecting whether a new function was defined, and (2) an LLM-based approach classifying commits into categories such as code development or maintenance.",
  "population_description": "For Python, Rust and Haskell packages, the study focused on the 2000 most popular packages as of 2021. For R packages, the entire list from the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) was obtained. Excluded were 348 Python packages, 7,965 R packages, 209 Rust packages and 42 Haskell packages that had not been updated in the two years preceding GitHub Copilot's release. After matching, the final dataset comprises 1,187 matched Python/R packages and 1,373 matched Rust/Haskell packages, aggregated at a quarterly level.",
