  "notes": "This is a natural experiment study using differences-in-differences with propensity score matching to estimate the causal impact of GitHub Copilot on open-source innovation. The study analyzes over 1.1 million commits across four programming languages (Python, R, Rust, Haskell) from October 2019 to December 2022. The paper distinguishes between two types of innovation: capability innovation (new feature development, measured by commits with new function definitions) and iterative innovation (maintenance and refinement, measured by commits without function additions). Key findings: GitHub Copilot increased overall contributions substantially (37-54% depending on language pair), but had a disproportionately larger effect on iterative/maintenance innovation compared to capability innovation. This gap widened further in high-activity projects and after the June 2022 model upgrade. Multiple robustness checks are reported using alternative specifications (balanced panel, synthetic difference-in-differences), log-transformed outcomes, and LLM-based commit categorization. The study notes several limitations: (1) the temporal boundary (October 2021 to December 2022) was necessary to maintain a clean natural experiment before ChatGPT's introduction; (2) not every contributor may have used Copilot, so findings likely represent a lower bound; (3) generalization to other innovation domains beyond open-source requires caution; (4) the paper documents differential impacts but notes that fully understanding the mechanisms requires further investigation. Propensity score matching was employed to address potential selection bias in language choice. Cohen's Kappa agreement for LLM-based categorization was above 0.6 for GPT-4o and Deepseek models, indicating substantial agreement.",
  "_paper_id": "doron"
}